file_name: XC197973-Chaffinch and Greenfinch flight calls, Bangor, 2014-09-02 1531hrs.mp3
remarks: As this recording is composed of virtually equal parts of calls from Greenfinch and Chaffinch, I have decided to upload it under both species. The calls are typical of both species in flight but, as here, the same sounds can be given when an individual is on the point of flying or animated (but still perched). The situation of the recording is worth explaining. I was in my own garden and had disturbed several Greenfinches and Chaffinches from a feeder. In fact, I had disturbed them because I was filling the feeder. The birds might have worked out that they did not need to fly away. Rather, I like to think that they moved a short distance into adjacent trees to await a chance to return. Luckily they called while perched high overhead. The Chaffinch's soft 'choop' call is its usual call-sign when in flight. Chaffinches passing overhead, for example in autumn, announce themselves by transmitting random choop notes. In fact, when several call separately, the overlap and close proximity of the individual notes can lead to some confusion and can suggest trills. At rest, choop is replaced by 'fink' (sometimes doubled). Good examples of the choop note are within the first second, just after 0:03 and just after 0:05. Unlike Chaffinch, Greenfinch employs a real trill. The burst contains homogenous notes and the sequence varies from (usually) three to six syllables. Good examples occur just after 0:01 and 0:08.

Este parque periurbano es una zona que se ha conseguido restaurar con diversas especies de árboles y vegetación riparia que rodea varias lagunas y el cauce de un arroyo. Las grabaciones a veces son más cortas de lo deseado porque el lugar se encuentra muy cerca del aeropuerto de Sevilla, de hecho se pueden ver los aviones aterrizando y despegando desde este parque, y esto perturba los audios. Actualmente este parque está en peligro debido a que se quiere destruír parte de él para hacer una nueva carretera.

remarks: Este pantano está rodeado de un buen bosque mediterráneo con acebuches y diferentes quercíneas entremezclado de vez en cuando con algún cortijo o estructura campestre humana. location: refugio de la serpiente, estepa, Sevilla, Andalucía
file_name: XC279660-chloris chloris refugio de la serpiente 13-06-2015.mp3
remarks: Un refugio natural en el que se han reabilitado cuatro hectáreas de terreno donde se ha plantado toda una variedad de vegetación mediterránea, se han instalado puntos de agua y comida para las aves (estos últimos sólo en invierno), se ha colocado una estación de anillamiento de aves que se utiliza regularmente y se ha restaurado una casa típica antigua. En Los alrededores hay serranía escarpada con Pinus alepensis y suelo calizo con matorral propio de este terreno, y una de las particularidades del lugar es que hay un abundante sotobosque de palmito y romero.

location: observatorio del acebrón, el rocío, huelva, andalucía
remarks: Una pareja de verderones llamando a un joven volandero que previamente había cruzado ante nosotros por el sendero. En este lugar se encuentra un gran palacio construído en la primera mitad del siglo XX. El entorno natural es un gran fragmento de bosque mediterráneo y pinar con un arroyo alrededor del cual crecen árboles típicos de ribera, helechos y lianas.

file_name: XC283450-chloris chloris refugio de la serpiente 17-07-2015.mp3
remarks: Las pausas corresponden a los momentos en los que la especie aparece. En un punto de agua por la mañana. Se puede oír gran número de cigarras Cicada Barbara cantando, y muchas abejas Apis Mellifera recogiendo agua. En este refugio se ha restaurado una casa antigua de pueblo, se han plantado árboles y se han instalado comederos, bebederos y una estación de anillamiento. Se están realizando gran cantidad de actividades en el lugar.

also: Turdus merula, Streptopelia decaocto, Chloris chloris, Passer domesticus
remarks:
Same as XC131681, XC131682 & XC131688 . Advertising song from vagrant first-summer male (aged by moult limit in primaries: outer 5 replaced in post-juvenile moult). Video of bird can be found [here](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lOu2UYhOA-I). 

Again, not the greatest recording (location very noisy), but uploaded because it illustrates the point that the order and number of notes can be varied. Recording unedited.

also: Chloris chloris
remarks: La llamada se parece mucho a la del verderón, Chloris Chloris, con los que van mezclados estos pinzones. En general la zona es un cauce de arroyo casi seco, a penas con algunos charcos por la poca precipitación que ha habido este otoño, rodeado de todo un mosaico de ecosistemas. En parte de las orillas persiste lo que sería la vegetación natural, que serían grandes álamos, tarajales y carrizos, pero los agricultores han mondado gran parte de la estructura vegetal del cauce. Más allá se alternan pinares, restos de alcornocales, eriales, algún viñedo y cercados para ganado. El tramo en el que está hecha la grabación conserva un tipido zarzal alternado con carrizales y algunos álamos dentro de esa maraña vegetal. Además concserva algo de corriente y dado que tuvo agua en lo peor del verano estuvo actuando de bebedero.

Perched Greenfinch delivering trill that is used at rest and in flight (when the sound is a standard flight call). Between 3 and 10 identical notes are given in such quick succession that a trill results. The notes are fairly 'hard-edged' and seem hammered together. As with trying to memorize all bird sounds, it helps to paint a picture in your mind's eye. Because each note in the sequence is identical, one analogy that might suggest the sound is a line of flats: the buildings' tall, repeated pattern could be used as a template corresponding to the sonogram of Greenfinch's trill.

remarks: ME 66 - K6 + Zoom H4N
ME 66 - K6 + Zoom H4N

Regular flight calls and 'courtship call' from a male Greenfinch.  The recording was made when I was not present - so I did not see the bird. However, the clip is from a perched Greenfinch and hence the wheezing courtship call was not delivered in flight. Given the time of year - and unusually cold weather -  none of the Greenfinches I see are bothering to perform song-flights - in which they broadcast the 'courtship wheeze'.  In summary, the clip contains the typical one-off call as well as the same note developed into a trill (which, like the one-off call, can be used at rest or in flight). After a series of calls - and one full-blown trill - the bird then utters its 'courtship wheeze' (five repetitions).  Also of interest is a calling Blue Tit (perhaps two).  Just before the Greenfinch gives its first wheeze, a Blue Tit produces a short piece of conversational sound (0:09, although it comes just before the tenth second). However, on the tail-end of each Greenfinch wheeze, the Blue Tit (I assume the same Blue Tit, although it is feasible that one Blue Tit called at the ninth second and was answered by a different Blue Tit  - maybe a pair was present). In any case, the Blue Tit's timing is uncanny - no sooner had the Greenfinch finished its wheeze than the Blue Tit tacked on its call, using the 'acoustic gap' after the Greenfinch. I have noticed this habit in many species - in this way, 'sonic crowding' is avoided.  By way of a summary, the clip contains: Greenfinch call notes containing two or three syllables at 0:01, 0:02 and 0:03 (the latter a series of four calls, each containing two or three syllables); a four-syllabled call at 0:06; full trill at 0:07; two- and three-syllabled calls at 0:08; wheezes at 0:10, 0:15, 0:18. 0:22 and 0:27. The Blue Tit's first utterance is at 0:09, thereafter it follows each of the Greenfinch's wheeze.

 ...4-6 birds seen while foraging...but i couldn't shure analyze the species.

---- ((in the park area are very nice birds ..and e.g. also a beaver. --- the birds are partly day-guests of the 2 km away {not so large} mixed forest)).

---- (( the residential areas are also with nice gardens and a lot of birds)).

remarks:
in city-habitat -- **sound was trapped for 2 hours** -NO! Bird-SEEN!!  ..... --- 05.11.2017...sunday morning between 07:00-9:15 a clock at my balcony...i tried to record the daily migration-flight of mixed Raven birds.
 -- the Turdus pilaris in district are at this time of the year, foraging here the berries of mountain ash.    ... . the Passer domesticus and the Streptopelia decaocto are through the whole year in my street.    .. and the Tits, the Common Blackbird, the Pica pica and the Wren are to hear (sometimes) in neighbours garden, all seasons, too.
....after about 01:15:00 hours there was excitement of all birds, couse a Hawk tries to hunt there in my district.    

here you hear all birds of this sunday at my balcony:    <http://www.xeno-canto.org/explore?query=rec%3A%22uhl%22+loc%3A%22Augsburg%2C+Vogelmauer+13%22+rmk%3A%2205.11.2017%22>

location: Lower Killeens Road, Cork, County Cork
file_name: XC564759-crystallised song from a Lesser Whitethroat near Cork city 1st June 2020_HH_stereo_1.mp3
also: Corvus frugilegus, Chloris chloris
remarks:
Two different song strophe types from a presumed male Lesser Whitethroat in an area of potential breeding habitat. No deliberate playback was attempted, so as not to disturb the bird, and it was singing and showing occasionally anyway, but it may have reacted to my brief listen back to a recording of it from a few minutes previously to see how it came out. I stopped that listen immediately in case that this had prompted a reaction.

  Interestingly, as well as the more typical 'rattle' strophes, this bird also habitually threw in another song strophe type reminiscent of a Coal Tit, perhaps, and which could be dismissed as 'just a tit' if heard out of context from an unseen bird. Whether this is innate, and part of the normal 'vocabulary' of the species, or actual mimicry of a Coal Tit, I don't know. 

  Lesser Whitethroat is a scarce passage migrant in Ireland, mainly being found on headlands and islands, and is commoner in autumn than spring, though always a good find anywhere. Sporadic breeding records have been proven, and the incidence of singing birds in spring seems to be increasing, but, of course, the twin combination of low observer density and reduced effort away from the hotspots could lead to under-recording of the true picture. In this case, I may not have walked by the area in which the bird is holding territory were it not for travel restrictions due to COVID-19, and certainly wouldn't have found it had it not sang. It effectively didn't show at all when found on 30th May, bar for one flight view.

   Notch filter applied below 250Hz, fade in and out applied also.

also: Dryocopus martius, Sitta europaea, Lullula arborea, Chloris chloris
remarks:
SNR: 59 dB(ISO/ITU)

Recorded:

  • song, schüppi-schüppi-schüppi-schüppi, at 0:01.7, 0:07.8, 0:13.5, 0:19.3, 0:25, 0:30.1, 0:35.6, 0:41.4, 0:48.2 and 0:53.8

Recording remarks: Cramp and Perrins (1993) distinguises three types of Marsh Tit song. The one recorded here seems to correspond to type 2, "slower repetition of 2-unit motif".

General observations: A couple of aspen grow close to a small field and a forest of mainly coniferous trees . A Marsh tit sings from the canopy of an aspen tree. Clear skies. Temperature: 8°C/46.4°F. Southwesterly moderate breeze.

Sound classification and rendering: Cramp, S. and Perrins, C. M. (ed.) (1993) The Birds of the Western Palearctic, Volume 7: Flycatchers to Shrikes. Oxford University Press, Oxford.

Other distinguishable species:

  • Black Woodpecker, Dryocopus martius, call, klije, at 0:01.5, 0:12 and 0:58.1; flight call, krrri krrri krrri, at e.g. 0:14.2 and 0:43.5
  • Woodlark, Lullula arborea, song, at e.g. 0:05.6, 0:10.4 and 1:04.5 (vaguely)
  • European Greenfinch, Chloris chlors, alarm call, diUwee, at e.g. 0:07.8 and 0:21.3 (vaguely)
  • Eurasian Nuthatch, Sitta europaea, whistle song, whee whee whee, at e.g. 0:13 and 0:18.1 (vaguely)

remarks:
sound-was-trapped .. in my attic-room in kursana from 5,15 a.m. first wake up of birds   ... till about 14,30 p.m. MEZ.

the birds are perched in a tree-margin infront of my window. -- here i upload as first 3 soundscapes ....the first 4 1/2 hours 

... herein is to hear a  kitchen exhaust pipe beneath my window with its sound .. and also our daily food-suplyment with truck and car at our kitchen in this back-house garden.

at around highnoon till 13,00 p.m. i made a short walk in my nearer residential-living area. -- these some cuts are recorded with my live comments of the recording situation. -- back home then in my attic-living-room i did again short some cuts from my window to the tree-line in our backhouse-garden.

...date/time **now: Wendsday --12,00 a.m. - 14,00 p.m. MEZ**

place: ( KUSAdomizyRoo-home-SESSI-oddZz-03 ) 

**here:**

also: Regulus ignicapilla, Fringilla coelebs, Turdus philomelos, Sylvia atricapilla, Troglodytes troglodytes, Chloris chloris
remarks:
Once da mañá nas Ribeiras do Sarela en Vista Alegre, Santiago.
 No primeiro plano, e presente en toda a gravación, un tordo  canta dende o alto dun ameneiro enchendo o espacio sonoro. Ao pouco, escoitase o canto descendente dun pimpín entre as doces frases afrautadas dunha papuxa das amoras. De súpeto, unha carriza enche o espacio sonoro  co seu potente canto e escoitamos os trilos lonxanos dun verderolo. No cuarto  final da gravación  varios cantos dunha estreliña riscada enchen as altas frecuencias .

also: Turdus merula, Sturnus unicolor, Chloris chloris
remarks: el aguacero ha cesado y gruesas gotas escurren de los edificios y de las hojas de los árboles. Un estornino comienza a cantar en su posadero habitual y unas parejas de verderón común retoman el cuidado de sus pollos los cuales solicitan alimento ruidosamente. En alguna parte un mirlo sale de su refugio en un matorral para aprovechar las lombrices que surgen a la superficie atraídas por la humedad. Más lejos se oyen las campanas de una iglesia. Grabación realizada en la zona ajardinada de un palacio en el casco histórico de Córdoba.

remarks:
" ..& 'buzzard call' of Garrulus glandarius "  --  in my home smalltown city-park ... --sound was trapped-- for 5-7 hours 

....weather was cloudy and windy and cold....

i puted my zoom h1N-1 in a trash tin box...{vegatable food} 

... and fastened this  at ground under a tall conifere.... the recording place is surrounded by vegatable-gardens ... a 90 m away street .. and here (part of this public park) .. a newer deadwood beatles-school-trail  .. made by bobinger peoples.

... i filtered the youngster voices in this park well....some times was strong working-noise to hear.

date/time **now:  tuesday 15.02.2022 --8,00 -10,30 a.m. ...MEZ** ...about. ....{... -this is batch-01-fichte}

place: (Kusa-east-gardens-IN-fichte-03-aa )

... batch worked filtered and recived with audacity .. in carefully way .. well i hope.

--- the cuts with the human-voices i filtered {more unusually} and stronger!!!

all recordings of this [vegetable-gardens fieldlane ....90 m east of street infront of our house elias.... hear here](https://xeno-canto.org/explore?query=rec:%20uhl%20rmk:%20east-gardens-IN%20loc:%20bobingen) .

remarks:
High-pass filter, noise reduction, and normalization applied.

Habitat: A small patch of reeds mixed with shrubs (but no open mud or water surface). Neighbouring a lowland river on one side (separated only by a grassy path and bank), and large open fields on the other side (separated only by a scattered row of trees. Far from any settlement.

The mystery sound was surprisingly loud (almost like a grey heron), coming from the thick reeds/shrubs. It would repeat now and then (sometimes with a break of over a minute). I could not see the animal. At first (from a distance), I suspected the common snipe, and so I played this recording back to the animal (https://macaulaylibrary.org/asset/388977431). It didn't react clearly or immediately; rather, it simply continued making the sounds some 20-30s later.
